I love children’s books, their illustrations inspire me and I cherish the memories my family made with me through reading.

Recently celebrated the one year anniversary of bringing this strange little muppet into my life.
Thank you to all of my friends and family that have been barked at, or growled at and have still made effort to help me give this guy another shot. 
He’s come so far and he’s getting so much better and friendlier. 
The love this creature and I share is unlike anything I have ever experienced, he brings me so much laughter, joy and companionship. When I see him finally getting more comfortable and snuggling with friends or taking treats and wagging for people it makes me so excited for his future. 
When Rudy first came to us he had an atrophied hurt leg and an off center jaw, indicating a severe trauma that occurred before we got him. We got him transformative leg surgery and truly watched him blossom into such a happy and energetic guy. 
He is learning to trust, and love and enjoy his life and I couldn’t be more proud. 
@casa_dogrescue

Welcome to the print shop!
This is where we print and process all of our hand screened goods.
This is why there are little imperfections or maybe a stray fuzz or string on your garments. Because we do it all from home! And we’re dang proud of it. 
Looking at this garage is like peering into the dreams of my past. This is my home, my life, my everything and every day. 
Truly my obsession and passion. 
I’m thrilled to share it and beyond grateful to be surviving off it.

🪡The JJV Queer Quilt Pride Flag!
For only $30! - I want this as affordable as possible.
🏳️‍🌈🏳️‍⚧️This project has been so close to my heart and I’m really proud of it.
The original drawing took hours of research and time to create, coloring it and choosing the shades took even more hours. Every part is special and means something. 
This design is inspired by queer representation in nature and vintage calico patchwork fabric. 
🏳️‍⚧️I have always wanted an alternative pride flag, and I’m ecstatic to have made my own and present it JUST in time for pride month. 
Plus there’s also a mug! And it’s a big mug!! I love it!!

Ten years ago I lived down the street from this abandoned house I would hang out at all the time, and one day I found a partially mummified raccoon that would inspire me to start drawing nocturnal animals with vacant eyes. Over time I defined my style and began my career in my true love, textile printing.
First by using styrofoam meat packages and acrylic paint to block print and then slowly into self taught screen printing. I made and sold patches for many years at local markets, every online craft hosting site you can think of. Slowly I experimented on tablecloths, napkins and used clothes. In 2020 I made the leap to full time art and delved into apparel and said goodbye to patches. 

In 2018 I learned to tattoo, primarily by self taught practices with the guidance of an old friend. In the aftermath of the pandemic, I soon learned it was not the full time career for me. Printing is my fixation, my serenity and my livelihood. 

Throughout my career I have loved acrylic painting, special tattoo projects and film photography. I go where my heart desires, do what I want, and I don’t comprise myself! 
I’m so thankful for the friends and family that have supported me and of course all the folks who have bought things from me.
Here’s to another decade! 
Thanks for coming along.

2023. I close my eyes and think about what happened this year. Somehow it feels like such a blur, a lot of time spent in bed, watching tv, working in the garage, burning screens and driving my car. This was a year of slow growth, reassessing, retreat, yearning. Sterling moments of outstretched hands, touching fingertips through tears, and staring into the sky farther than before.
This year was a lonesome drive, broken up by passengers who break the silence with cackling seconds of connection.
I craved deeper relationships, but was drawn inward more often than not. I felt conflicted as to if I was wasting my life by staying in and working, living and toiling from home. 
Letting myself rest, letting go of guilt and shame again and again, even after I had thought the work was done. 
Admitting to myself that I don’t have it figured out.
That I can apologize, I can forgive myself and others.
Ultimately, I am finding balance and learning my limitations. Learning not to compare myself, to accept my neurodivergence and be kinder to myself. 
I can be stern without anger, and strong in myself. Strong enough to protect my softness and offer it again and again. 
Softness, tenderness, compassion, these are the things I want to remember in every aspect of my life. The things I want to choose when given the option.
I want to carry the patience I have been afforded and reapply it to my interactions. To remember the ways in which I have been hurt and make the choice to end the cycles that have harmed me and others.
I want to remember that I will never have it figured out, and there is an excitement, a humbling to the discovery ahead. 

This year I want to reconnect with myself, with my heart and the things I truly love, the people I love. Make art for the sake of art. 
I want to be with my friends in silence and laughter, painting next to one another, playing guitar in the next room.
This is long winded, it’s not the reflection I had intended to write, but it’s an honest one. 
I feel deeply grateful yet unfulfilled, agitated, wanting. Afraid to peer into the hole and see what’s at the bottom. Maybe that’s most of us. 
Anyway, cheers. Thanks for being here.
